thers beyond colonial modes of empathy. Davis illustrates that moving beyond empathy allows for a more nuanced understanding of the colonial past and its ongoing impact while providing for a more meaningful affective engagement with the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aColonizationxSocial aspects. 0aEmpathy. 0aHuman zoosxHistoryy19th century. 0aOther (Philosophy)xSocial aspects. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aRacism in anthropologyxHistory. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027010?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027010423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027010/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles